revision.text:
The '''Ahuroa Gas Storage Facility''' is an underground [[natural gas storage]] facility situated at Ahuroa in the [[Taranaki region]] of [[New Zealand]], owned by Gas Services New Zealand.<ref>{{cite news| first=Rob| last=Maetzi| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/business/4475776/Underground-gas-storage-site-gets-nod| title=Underground gas storage site gets nod| date=20 December 2010| publisher=Taranaki Daily News}}</ref> It was officially opened in 2011.<ref>{{cite news| first=John| last=Anthony| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/national/5082847| title=Power plant fires up in 10 minutes| date=1 June 2011| publisher=Fairfax NZ News}}</ref> The development cost of the facility was $177m.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.stuff.co.nz/taranaki-daily-news/business/8812153/New-exploration-plan-for-old-wells| title=New exploration plan for old wells| date=19 June 2013| first=Rob| last=Maetzig| publisher=Taranaki Daily News}}</ref> The stored gas is used to supply the [[Stratford Power Station]] when needed during peak electricity demand. Gas can be stored by injection at up to 32 terajoules per day and withdrawn at up to 45 terajoules per day.<ref>{{cite press release| url=https://www.contact.co.nz/Assets/pdfs/corporate/web-prints/web-20110531.pdf| title=Contact Energy opens $400 million development in Taranaki| publisher=Contact Energy| date=31 May 2011}}</ref>
==History== The Tariki / Ahuroa field was discovered in 1986. Construction of wellsite facilities began in 1995 and production commenced in 1996.<ref>{{cite conference|url=http://www.nzpam.govt.nz/cms/pdf-library/petroleum-conferences-1/1998-petroleum-conference-proceedings/GLogan_development_engineering.pdf |title=Development and Engineering Highlights in 1996/1997 |first=Geoff |last=Logan |date=30 March 1998 |conference=1998 New Zealand Petroleum Conference |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130223202833/https://www.nzpam.govt.nz/cms/pdf-library/petroleum-conferences-1/1998-petroleum-conference-proceedings/GLogan_development_engineering.pdf |archivedate=23 February 2013 }}</ref> The facility was in turn owned by [[Fletcher Challenge]], Shell and Swift Energy.
In 2008, when the field was largely depleted, it was acquired by [[Origin Energy]] as part of the Tariki / Ahuroa / Waihapa / Ngaere assets. The gas storage facility was constructed by [[Contact Energy]] in 2009 and 2010.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.newzealandenergy.com/files/doc_presentations/NZECPPT-StrategicAcquisition.pdf| title=Strategic Taranaki Acquisition| publisher=[[New Zealand Energy Corporation]]| date=11 July 2013}}</ref>
In 2017, Contact Energy sold the gas storage facility to Gas Services New Zealand.<ref>{{cite press release| url=https://www.nzx.com/announcements/312253| title=Contact Energy to sell AGS to Gas Services New Zealand| publisher=Contact Energy| date=21 December 2017}}</ref>
